const a = [
  {"id":3764,"text":"A patient is on heparin, which is an anticoagulant. In case of heparin overdose, bleeding can occur. This bleeding can be controlled by administering which of the following drugs as an antidote to this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 278.","responses":[{"text":"Hydroxocobalamin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcysteine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protamine sulfate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascorbic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylene blue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3765,"text":"What is the process in which antigen-antibody (Ag-Ab) complexes are phagocytosed much more efficiently in the presence of C3b known as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 205-206.","responses":[{"text":"Cytolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemotoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opsonization","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaphylatoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysis of bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3766,"text":"Alpha thalassemia presents in four different clinical conditions because of the presence of how many copies of genes?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 641.","responses":[{"text":"5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3768,"text":"\"A thymus-derived cell that participates in a variety of cell mediated immune reactions\". Which cell does this statement define?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 275-276.","responses":[{"text":"Monocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-cell","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural killer cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polymorphonuclear cell","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3770,"text":"Which system reaches the functional state first in the embryo?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 63.","responses":[{"text":"Nervous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excretory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiovascular","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Skeletal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3771,"text":"A woman has a mechanical heart valve and takes warfarin. What advice should she receive regarding her anti-thrombotic medication in pregnancy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 277, 280.","responses":[{"text":"Warfarin should be replaced with aspirin at high doses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All the medications that affect the blood should be avoided","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin should be replaced with heparin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin should be discontinued and supplementary vitamin A should be taken everyday throughout the pregnancy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin should be discontinued until the third trimester","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3773,"text":"A young male brought to the emergency room was in an unconscious state following an injection dose of a medicine given by a general practitioner. On examination, the patient was diagnosed with anaphylactic shock. Which of the following is the main causative factor for the mentioned condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 97.","responses":[{"text":"B-lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antigen presenting cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3775,"text":"Which of the following is inhibited by aminocaproic acid?","explanation":null,"reference":"Griffin JD, Ellman L. Epsilon-aminocaproic acid (Eaca). Seminars in Thrombosis and Hemostasis. Published 1978. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/568312/","responses":[{"text":"Warfarin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antiplatelet drugs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinolytic drugs","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3777,"text":"Which of the following is the most abundant plasma protein?","explanation":null,"reference":"Campos Munoz A, Jain NK, Gupta M. Albumin colloid. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 30, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534241/","responses":[{"text":"Albumin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peptones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peptide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3778,"text":"An outbreak of septicemia by Staphylococcus aureus occurred in a children's ward. Where is the causative organism usually found as part of the normal flora?","explanation":null,"reference":"1. Savolainen S, Ylikoski J, Jousimies-Somer H. The bacterial flora of the nasal cavity in healthy young men. Rhinology. Published December 1986. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3547601","responses":[{"text":"Lower respiratory tract","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nose","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrointestinal tract","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Throat","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3780,"text":"Aspirin differs from other nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) in what aspect?","explanation":null,"reference":"Meek IL, van de Laar MAFJ, Vonkeman HE. Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs: an overview of cardiovascular risks. Pharmaceuticals. Published July 7, 2010. Accessed May 30, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4036661/","responses":[{"text":"Unlike other NSAIDs, aspirin can arrest the progress of arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Analgesic action of aspirin is due to the decrease in PGE₂ synthesis while other NSAIDs have no action on this prostaglandin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unlike other NSAIDs, aspirin inhibits both the cyclooxygenase and lipoxygenase pathways","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unlike aspirin, NSAIDs are reversible inhibitors of cyclooxygenase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial nephritis can only result from aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3806,"text":"Through which process do reticulocytes enter peripheral blood circulation from bone marrow?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Phagocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Margination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemotaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diapedesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pinocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3817,"text":"How does aspirin inhibit platelet aggregation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 661.","responses":[{"text":"Because it inhibits TXA₂ production in platelets for 3 - 7 days","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When it is given at 60 - 80 g/day doses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By irreversible inhibition of cyclooxygenase pathway in endothelial cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"By reversible inhibition of cyclooxygenase pathway for the lifetime of the platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By irreversible inhibition of lipooxygenase pathway","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3818,"text":"What does a bacteriostatic agent do?","explanation":null,"reference":"Loree J, Lappin SL. Bacteriostatic antibiotics. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 30, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK547678/","responses":[{"text":"Maintains human cell growth rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits the growth of bacteria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"No effect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Slows viral growth rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases growth rate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3819,"text":"Before cell division, the final check point for DNA damage/abnormality occurs at which phase of the cell cycle?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 289.","responses":[{"text":"G1 / S","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"M","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"G2 / M","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"G1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"G2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3820,"text":"What is Blackwater fever a complication of?","explanation":null,"reference":"Shanks GD. The multifactorial epidemiology of blackwater fever. The American Journal of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene. Published December 6, 2017. Accessed May 30, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5805072/","responses":[{"text":"Ovale malaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoebic dysentery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dengue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vivax malaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Falciparum malaria","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3821,"text":"Cancer cells have limitless proliferative capacities because of which of the following mechanisms?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 67.","responses":[{"text":"Cellular senescence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitotic catastrophe","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in apoptosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased IGF resulting in angiogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upregulation of the enzyme telomerase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3822,"text":"What is the cancerous mutation of myelogenous or lymphogenous cells called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davis AS, Viera AJ, Mead MD. Leukemia: an overview for primary care. American Family Physician. Published May 1, 2014. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24784336/","responses":[{"text":"Thrombocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukemoid reaction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukemia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3823,"text":"Which of the following regarding ceruloplasmin is correct?","explanation":null,"reference":"Roeser HP, Lee GR, Nacht S, Cartwright GE. The role of ceruloplasmin in iron metabolism. The Journal of Clinical Investigation. Published December 1970. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/5480864","responses":[{"text":"Involved in Zn absorption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Changes Fe⁺² to Fe⁺³","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Present in neurons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acts primarily in muscle cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Converts hemoglobin to myoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3824,"text":"Which of these is a clotting factor that requires activation and is dependent on vitamin K?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 480, 485.","responses":[{"text":"Calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Labile factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue factor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3825,"text":"Defensins are highly positively charged cationic peptides that perform which of the following functions?","explanation":null,"reference":"Xu D, Lu W. Defensins: a double-edged sword in host immunity. Frontiers in Immunology. Published May 7, 2020. Accessed June 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7224315/","responses":[{"text":"Activate complement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Create pores in bacterial membrane","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cause opsonization of bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Help in the formation of superoxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3826,"text":"What is deferoxamine a specific antidote of?","explanation":null,"reference":"Velasquez J, Wray AA. Deferoxamine. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 31, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557654/","responses":[{"text":"Antiplatelet drugs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinolytic drugs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3827,"text":"What does a deficiency of factor VIII cause?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 485.","responses":[{"text":"Thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polycythemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia B","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3837,"text":"Epstein-Barr virus causes which type of malignancy in African children?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 327.","responses":[{"text":"Leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Burkitt's lymphoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral T-cell lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mastocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3838,"text":"What combination of blood groups leads to erythroblastosis fetalis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 447.","responses":[{"text":"When the mother is Rh- and fetus is Rh+","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"When the mother is B+ and fetus is O+","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When the mother is AB+ and fetus is AB-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When the mother is O+ and fetus is O-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When the mother is A+ and fetus is B-","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3839,"text":"The fibroblast used to heal wounds is derived from which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 96.","responses":[{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Local mesenchyme","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vascular fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3840,"text":"Where does the first step of red blood cell formation normally occur in an adult?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphoid tissues","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3842,"text":"What does glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase do?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 634.","responses":[{"text":"Oxidizes NADPH to NADP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduces NADPH to NADP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduces NADP to NADPH","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduces ATP to ADP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxidizes NADP to NADPH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3843,"text":"Glycine and succinyl CoA combine to form delta-aminolevulinic acid in the presence of which enzyme?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 278.","responses":[{"text":"Esterase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hexokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delta aminolevulinic acid synthase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyruvate kinase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3844,"text":"What are growth factors usually made of?","explanation":null,"reference":"Stone WL, Leavitt L, Varacallo M. Physiology, growth factor. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 31, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK442024/","responses":[{"text":"Carbohydrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aminoglycosides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycoproteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polypeptides","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3845,"text":"Hemolytic disease of newborn due to Rh incompatibility is caused by which type of hypersensitivity?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 205.","responses":[{"text":"Complement mediated","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaphylactic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contact type","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotoxic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune complex mediated","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3846,"text":"How does histamine cause increased vascular leakage?","explanation":null,"reference":"umar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 74.","responses":[{"text":"Endothelial cell necrosis and detachment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased trancytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased hydrostatic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased margination of leukocytes at the site of injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contraction of endothelial cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3847,"text":"Human T-cell leukemia virus type-1 (HTLV-1) affects which inflammatory cells?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 325.","responses":[{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CD2+ T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CD4+ T-cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3848,"text":"Which of the following is a unique stain used in histological studies?","explanation":null,"reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 73,74,75.","responses":[{"text":"Neutrophilia (pink stain) for neutrophil granules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophilia (blue stain) for DNA in ribosomes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia (red stain) for hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophilia (yellow stain) for hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Azurophilia (purple stain) for lysosome of WBCs","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3849,"text":"For malaria, sporozoites are injected into humans beings. The exo-erythrocytic cycle takes place in which organ of the body?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 390.","responses":[{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymph node","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3883,"text":"In malignant tumors, what does the term \"loss of polarity\" mean?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 270.","responses":[{"text":"Formation of tumors against normal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleomorphism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"More than 10 mitoses/10 high power fields","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Altered nuclear cytoplasmic ratio of cancer cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Markedly disturbed orientation of cancer cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3884,"text":"In reticuloendothelial cells, what initially degrades heme?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 875.","responses":[{"text":"Dehydratase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heme oxygenase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Biliverdin reductase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferrochelatase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3886,"text":"Innate immunity is considered to be the first line of defense against many microorganisms. Which of the following is a major component of this immunity?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 459.","responses":[{"text":"T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3887,"text":"How can iron be  rapidly depleted from the body?","explanation":null,"reference":"Warner MJ, Kamran MT. Iron deficiency anemia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 3, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448065/","responses":[{"text":"High altitude","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight loss","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High calcium absorption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood loss","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vigorous exercise","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3888,"text":"Kala-azar is found in most tropical and subtropical countries and is transferred by the sand-fly. What is its causative organism?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 390.","responses":[{"text":"T. cruzi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L. tropica","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L. braziliensis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L. mexicana","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L. donovani","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3889,"text":"What condition are macro-ovalocytes in a peripheral blood smear seen in?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 645.","responses":[{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hereditary spherocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3894,"text":"What is the mechanism of action of penicillin?","explanation":null,"reference":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3881775","responses":[{"text":"Inhibition of transpeptidation in the cell wall","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of beta-lactamase in the cell wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of endogenous phospholipases, destroying bacterial cell wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of endogenous proteases, destroying bacterial cell wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of exogenous proteases, destroying bacterial cell wall","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3895,"text":"Which of the following is a major mediator of an anaphylactic reaction?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 97.","responses":[{"text":"Slow-reacting substance of anaphylaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serotonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotriene","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3896,"text":"Which of these is the most appropriate technique for identifying thalassemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5760065/","responses":[{"text":"Estimation of shape hemoglobin molecules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin chromatography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measurement of iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measurement of mean corpuscular volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin electrophoresis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3897,"text":"What is the movement of leukocytes to the site of an injurious stimulus called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 87.","responses":[{"text":"Rolling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adhesion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Margination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemotaxis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diapedesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3898,"text":"What is the normal percentage of neutrophils in the adult human?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 449.","responses":[{"text":"20 - 30%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0 - 10%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30 - 40%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"60 - 70%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"80 - 90%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3899,"text":"What is 1 gram of pure hemoglobin capable of combining with?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 439.","responses":[{"text":"13.4 ml of carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.34 ml of oxygen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"134 ml of oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"13.4 ml of oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.34 ml of carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3900,"text":"Which one of the following substances is found in the specific cytoplasmic granules of neutrophils?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 80.","responses":[{"text":"Cationic proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myeloperoxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysozyme","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3901,"text":"Which of the following is most likely to lead to a patient presenting with bleeding?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 656.","responses":[{"text":"High platelet count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolonged bed rest or immobilization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protein S deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protein C deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low platelet count","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4013,"text":"How does penicillin kill bacterial cells?","explanation":null,"reference":"Yip DW, Gerriets V. Penicillin. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 3, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554560/","responses":[{"text":"By inhibiting the transpeptidation reaction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"By inhibiting the 50S ribosomal RNA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By inhibiting the folic acid synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By inhibiting the tubulin polymerization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By inhibiting the 30S ribosomal RNA","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4015,"text":"What causes pernicious anemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 206.","responses":[{"text":"Inadequate diet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid antagonists","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deficiency of intrinsic factor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vegetarianism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemodialysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4018,"text":"Pleomorphic adenoma is the swelling of the parotid gland and is an example of what?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 268.","responses":[{"text":"Mixed malignant tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Benign epithelial cell tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Painful, fast growing inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignant tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Benign mixed tumor","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4021,"text":"Porphyria results in the accumulation of a unique pattern of intermediates caused by the deficiency of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Gounden V, Jialal I. Acute porphyria. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 3, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537352/","responses":[{"text":"Intermediate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Succinyl CoA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enzyme","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4022,"text":"Regarding blood grouping, what does an Rh-positive individual possess?","explanation":null,"reference":"Costumbrado J, Mansour T, Ghassemzadeh S. Rh incompatibility. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 2, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459353/","responses":[{"text":"Agglutinogen D","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Agglutinin D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Agglutinogen A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Agglutinogen B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Agglutinin AB","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4027,"text":"Regarding carcinogens, which of the following statements is correct?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 323.","responses":[{"text":"No promotor is required for direct acting chemical carcinogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Most of the known carcinogens are metabolized by cytochrome P-450","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"All carcinogens are some form of ionic radiation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All carcinogens are manmade","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Man cannot manufacture carcinogens","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4030,"text":"Which of the following regarding HbH is correct?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 641.","responses":[{"text":"Iron overload is usually seen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia is moderately severe","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Results because of gene deletion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caused by the deletion of three α-globin genes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Not as severe as β-thalassemia major","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4033,"text":"Regarding signalling mechanisms in cell growth, what does \"autocrine signalling\" mean?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 16.","responses":[{"text":"Cell responding to signalling molecules that are secreted by far away cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cell responding to signalling molecules brought by blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cell responding to signalling molecules that they themselves secreted","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cell responding to signalling molecules brought by lymphatics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cell responding to signalling molecules that are secreted by adjacent cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4050,"text":"Why might cancer stem cells be less susceptible to chemotherapy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Yano S, Miwa S, Mii S, et al. Invading cancer cells are predominantly in G 0 /G 1 resulting in chemoresistance demonstrated by real-time FUCCI imaging. Cell Cycle. Published March 15, 2014. Accessed June 14, 2022. http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.4161/cc.27818","responses":[{"text":"Because of tumor debulking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Because of distant metastasis of tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cells are mostly in G₀ phase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth rate equals that of adjacent normal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Because of local tumor invasion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4056,"text":"Reiter's syndrome is a systemic autoimmune disease triggered by infection with intestinal pathogen. Which triad characterizes this disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Wu IB, Schwartz RA. Reiter’s syndrome: the classic triad and more. Journal of the American Academy of Dermatology. Published July 2008. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18436339.","responses":[{"text":"Conjuctivitis, arthritis, cervicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthritis, oophoritis, thydroiditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thydroiditis, tonsilitis, conjuctivitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthritis, conjuctivitis, urethritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cervicitis, arthritis, pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4061,"text":"What causes sickle cell disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 36.","responses":[{"text":"Increased synthesis of normal hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Replacement of valine by a glutamic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased synthesis of abnormal hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased synthesis of beta chain of globin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Point mutation in the 6th codon of the beta globin chain","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4065,"text":"The special propensity to collect in tissues undergoing allergic reactions is demonstrated by which of the following types of WBCs?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 96, 97.","responses":[{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4068,"text":"The sum of the squared deviations from the mean, when divided by the number of observations will give what value?","explanation":null,"reference":"El Omda S, Sergent SR. Standard deviation. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 14, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK574574/","responses":[{"text":"Mean deviation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Standard error","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Variance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Median","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Standard deviation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4069,"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus, a systemic autoimmune disease is caused by the formation of antibodies against which structure?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 207.","responses":[{"text":"Nerves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nuclear proteins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"RBCs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4078,"text":"Formation of which of the following is the rate-controlling factor in the coagulation process?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 479.","responses":[{"text":"Fibrin-stabilizing factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin activator","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium ions (K+)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium ions (Ca++)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4081,"text":"In hemoglobin C (HbC), which amino acid is substituted for glutamate?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karna B, Jha SK, Al Zaabi E. Hemoglobin c disease. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 1, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559043/","responses":[{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoleucine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Leucine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Valine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4173,"text":"In the formation of hemoglobin, which enzyme is involved in the incorporation of Fe into protoporphyrin IX?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1)Ferrochelatase - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 2, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/ferrochelatase (2)Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 279.","responses":[{"text":"ALA dehydratase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen III decarboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferroxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen III synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferrochelatase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4180,"text":"Which one of the following plays a vital role in the maturation of red blood cells?","explanation":null,"reference":"1. Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020.","responses":[{"text":"Thiamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyanocobalamin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4184,"text":"After how many days are platelets replaced?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 450.","responses":[{"text":"17 days","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5-7 days","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"8-10 days","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"13-15 days","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30-35 days","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4195,"text":"What is the other name for cobalamin?","explanation":null,"reference":"O’Leary F, Samman S. Vitamin b12 in health and disease. Nutrients. Published March 5, 2010. Accessed June 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3257642/","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin B-12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B-6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B-9","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4211,"text":"On the surface of which of these are type A, type B, and Rh antigens present?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dean L. Blood Group Antigens Are Surface Markers on the Red Blood Cell Membrane. National Center for Biotechnology Information (US); 2005. Accessed June 1, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK2264/","responses":[{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythrocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megakaryocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4218,"text":"How many pyrrole rings are present in one molecule of hemoglobin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 277.","responses":[{"text":"4 pyrrole rings","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"7 pyrrole rings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No pyrrole ring","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 pyrrole rings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6 pyrrole rings","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4219,"text":"In hemoglobin S (HbS), which amino acid residue is substituted by valine at the sixth position of the beta-globin chain?","explanation":"In **hemoglobin S (HbS)**, the amino acid residue that is substituted by valine at the sixth position of the beta-globin chain is **glutamate**. This substitution results in the formation of abnormal hemoglobin that can polymerize and cause red blood cells to sickle in certain conditions, leading to **sickle cell disease**.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 635.","responses":[{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoleucine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4220,"text":"Activated platelets undergo degranulation to release ADP and enzymes. Which of the following is formed by those enzymes?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 478.","responses":[{"text":"ATP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endothelin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4221,"text":"Which one of the following is activated by interleukin 5 (IL-5)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 198.","responses":[{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4240,"text":"Which of the following is the most appropriate measure of association for a case-control study?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 258.","responses":[{"text":"Death-to-case ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Odds ratio","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rate ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Risk ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevalence ratio","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4241,"text":"Which one of the following is the most important factor in opsonization?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 465.","responses":[{"text":"C3a","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5a","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5b","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C3b","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4247,"text":"Which one of the following models of disease causation involves a susceptible host, an external agent, and an environment that brings these two together?","explanation":null,"reference":"van Seventer JM, Hochberg NS. Principles of infectious diseases: transmission, diagnosis, prevention, and control. International Encyclopedia of Public Health. Published 2017. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7150340/","responses":[{"text":"Wheel of disease causation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Germ theory of disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemiologic triad","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Web of causation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sufficient-component cause model","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4252,"text":"In the complement system, which one is the most important chemotactic agent?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 465.","responses":[{"text":"C3b","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C9b","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5a","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C7b","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C8a","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4260,"text":"The activity of antithrombin III is increased by 100 to 1000 folds by binding to which of the following molecules?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 485.","responses":[{"text":"Heparin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protamine sulfate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4261,"text":"Glycosylated hemoglobin test (HbA1C) levels can be measured to diagnose which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 987, 988.","responses":[{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes insipidus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia B","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4262,"text":"Where is the value of mean located in a positively skewed curve?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 265.","responses":[{"text":"To the extreme right of the distribution","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"To the extreme left of the distribution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Between the median and the mode","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the highest peak of distribution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the middle of the peak","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4263,"text":"Deficiency of which of the following causes the hemorrhagic disease of the newborn?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kher P, Verma RP. Hemorrhagic disease of newborn. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 4, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK558994/","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin B-6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B-12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B-9","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4264,"text":"While observing under his microscope, a histologist noticed a few biconcave and disc-like cells under his microscope. What did he name them?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 439.","responses":[{"text":"Erythrocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megakaryocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4265,"text":"The clot is failing to retract. Defect in which of the following would be the likely cause?","explanation":"**Clot retraction** is primarily a function of **platelets**. Platelets play a crucial role in the process of clot retraction, where they contract and pull the edges of the wound closer together, reducing the size of the clot. Platelet contraction is mediated by actin and myosin interactions within the platelets. Defects in platelet function or number can impair clot retraction and lead to inadequate wound healing.","reference":"Jansen EE, Hartmann M. Clot retraction: cellular mechanisms and inhibitors, measuring methods, and clinical implications. Biomedicines. Published August 21, 2021. Accessed June 4, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8394358/","responses":[{"text":"T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelets","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4266,"text":"What is the square root of variance called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 265.","responses":[{"text":"T-test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mean deviation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Variance coefficient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Range","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Standard deviation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4267,"text":"The scar is formed by the process of pathological wound healing. What would its nature be?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 95.","responses":[{"text":"Collagen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Necrotic tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dead tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrotic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4268,"text":"Which antibody is most likely to pass from the maternal circulation to the fetus through the placenta?","explanation":null,"reference":"Palmeira P, Quinello C, Silveira-Lessa AL, Zago CA, Carneiro-Sampaio M. IgG placental transfer in healthy and pathological pregnancies. Clinical \u0026 Developmental Immunology. Published 2012. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22235228","responses":[{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4269,"text":"Where are most of the body's iron reserves found?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 891.","responses":[{"text":"Ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4280,"text":"What causes hemolysis in G6PD deficiency?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 634.","responses":[{"text":"Spherocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of Heinz bodies","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spectrin deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excess of alpha globin chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemosiderosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4282,"text":"Which of the following statements is true for the term \"carrier\"?","explanation":null,"reference":"Carrier state - mesh - ncbi. Accessed June 4, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?Db=mesh\u0026Cmd=DetailsSearch\u0026Term=%22Carrier+State%22%5BMeSH+Terms%5D","responses":[{"text":"An individual who is a carrier can carry a greater load than normal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"An individual who harbors a potential pathogen and can be a source of infection to others","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"An individual who is asymptomatic and thus cannot transmit any infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A carrier is one who harbors a usual pathogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"An individual with pathogens in sites that are normally colonized in others","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4283,"text":"What is the generation time of Escherichia coli in a lab?","explanation":null,"reference":"Gibson B, Wilson DJ, Feil E, Eyre-Walker A. The distribution of bacterial doubling times in the wild. Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences. Published June 13, 2018. Accessed June 4, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6015860/","responses":[{"text":"20 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 minutes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"20 days","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4284,"text":"What is an important feature of acute inflammation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 73.","responses":[{"text":"Accumulation of B-cells at the site of injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased blood flow in vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transmigration of the plasma, and red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of RBC to eliminate the offending agent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Changes in microvasculature","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4285,"text":"What is the major form of vitamin B12 found in human tissue and mitochondria?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kapadia CR. Vitamin B12 in health and disease: part I--inherited disorders of function, absorption, and transport. The Gastroenterologist. Published December 1995. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8775094/","responses":[{"text":"Hydroxycobalamin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrocobalamin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyanocobalamin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylcobalamin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5'-Deoxyadenosyl cobalamin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4286,"text":"What is the major source of histamine?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 215.","responses":[{"text":"Erythrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4288,"text":"What are the mesenchymal cells that aggregate to form blood islands?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia M. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 9th ed. Elsevier; 2011: 64.","responses":[{"text":"Definitive heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemoblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibroblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angioblasts","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesoblasts","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4290,"text":"What complication of thrombocytopenia is most likely to cause fatality?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 657.","responses":[{"text":"Needle prick","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gum bleeding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastro-intestinal bleeding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nose bleeding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracranial bleeding","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4292,"text":"What is the most common cause of a defect in leukocyte function?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Inherited defect in leukocyte adhesion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow suppression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inherited defect in phagolysosome function","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chediak-Higashi syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inherited defect in microbial activity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4305,"text":"What is the process of formation of the formed (solid) elements of blood called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 993.","responses":[{"text":"Erythropoiesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Homeostasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemostasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematopoiesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukopoiesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4306,"text":"What is the time between exposure and occurrence of the first symptom of a disease called?","explanation":null,"reference":"1. Linton NM, Kobayashi T, Yang Y, et al. Incubation period and other epidemiological characteristics of 2019 novel coronavirus infections with right truncation: a statistical analysis of publicly available case data. Journal of Clinical Medicine. Published February 17, 2020. Accessed June 4, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7074197/","responses":[{"text":"Serial interview","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exposure period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Window period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Generation time","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incubation period","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4307,"text":"Warfarin antagonizes the effect of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Patel S, Singh R, Preuss CV, Patel N. Warfarin. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 4, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470313/","responses":[{"text":"Tocopherol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascorbic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B6","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4317,"text":"Which cardinal sign of inflammation is less easily detected?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Increase in temperature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loss of function","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tenderness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pain","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4325,"text":"What would a disease that occurs in a certain geographical area and is meant to remain there be classified as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kalra S, Kumar A, Jarhyan P, Unnikrishnan AG. Endemic or epidemic? Measuring the endemicity index of diabetes. Indian Journal of Endocrinology and Metabolism. Published 2015. Accessed June 4, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4287779/","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zoonotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4326,"text":"Which of the following is the most important copper-containing protein?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 80.","responses":[{"text":"Cytochrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ceruloplasmin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4332,"text":"What is the correlation between the probability of an outcome in an exposed group to that in an unexposed group called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Tenny S, Hoffman MR. Relative risk. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 4, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430824/","responses":[{"text":"Relative risk","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic threshold","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Attack rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population-at-risk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevalence risk","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4333,"text":"Iron absorption occurs in which part of the gut?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 650.","responses":[{"text":"Ileum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal duodenum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4335,"text":"Which one of the following is a malignant tumor?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 268.","responses":[{"text":"Osteoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesothelioma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chondroma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leiomyoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibroma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4339,"text":"In which of the following modes of disease transmission does the infection spread either by skin-to-skin or mucosa-to-skin contact?","explanation":null,"reference":"Antonovics J, Wilson AJ, Forbes MR, et al. The evolution of transmission mode. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences. Published May 5, 2017. Accessed June 4, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5352810/","responses":[{"text":"Vertical transmission","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Air-borne droplet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Direct contact","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect contact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inoculation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4340,"text":"Which of the following plasma proteins plays the greatest role in maintaining the oncotic pressure?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 199.\r\n\"Oncotic pressure= colloid osmotic pressure.\"","responses":[{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Apolipoprotein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4341,"text":"Which of the following plasma proteins has the most prominent role in the transportation of free fatty acids?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 181.","responses":[{"text":"Plasma ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4342,"text":"Which of the following substances released by platelets plays a role in vasoconstriction?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 85.","responses":[{"text":"Prostacyclin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ATP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrous oxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4343,"text":"Activation of which of the following factors results in the initiation of the coagulation cascade through the intrinsic pathway?","explanation":"The activation of **Factor XII** (also known as Hageman factor) results in the initiation of the coagulation cascade through the intrinsic pathway. Factor XII is a clotting factor that plays a key role in the intrinsic pathway of coagulation.\r\n\r\nIn the intrinsic pathway, Factor XII is activated by contact with negatively charged surfaces, such as exposed collagen or subendothelial structures. Once activated, Factor XII initiates a cascade of reactions that ultimately lead to the formation of a blood clot. This cascade involves the activation of several other clotting factors, including Factor XI, Factor IX, and Factor VIII.\r\n\r\nActivation of the intrinsic pathway is important for amplifying the coagulation process and forming a stable blood clot. It occurs primarily in response to vascular injury or exposure of blood to foreign surfaces.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 482.","responses":[{"text":"Factor XII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4344,"text":"Which of the following chemical mediators is involved in chemotaxis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 90.","responses":[{"text":"Leukotriene B4 and bacterial products","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotriene C4, D4, E4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Substance P","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4345,"text":"Which one of the following is not a clinical feature of thrombocytopenia?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Bleeding in joints","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Petechial hemorrhages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ecchymosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bruises","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epistaxis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4346,"text":"Which of the following is a characteristic feature of severe iron deficiency anemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 652.","responses":[{"text":"Poikilocytosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elliptocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperchromia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Schistocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4347,"text":"Which of the following mediates cancer cachexia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 330.","responses":[{"text":"TNF-α","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IL-2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IL-5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"TGF-β","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CCl-5","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4348,"text":"Which of the following microorganisms is closely associated with dental caries?","explanation":null,"reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 29.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus epidermidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria gonorrhoea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus mutans","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Candida albicans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevolta melaninogenica","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4349,"text":"Which of the following sites of the human body does not usually have normal flora?","explanation":null,"reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 26.","responses":[{"text":"Vagina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal urethra","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4350,"text":"Which of the following cells are a dominant feature of the thymic medulla?","explanation":null,"reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 131.","responses":[{"text":"Thymocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hassall's corpuscles (thymic corpuscles)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphoblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4351,"text":"Which one of the following is an oral third generation cephalosporin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Leggett NJ, Caravaggio C, Rybak MJ. Cefixime. DICP: the annals of pharmacotherapy. Published May 1990. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2188437/","responses":[{"text":"Ceftizoxime","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cefazidime","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cefotaxime","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ceftriaxone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cefixime","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4352,"text":"A 9-month-old girl has been having recurrent infections since she was 2 months old and her\r\nsister complains of a similar history. They were both the children of a consanguineous marriage. Which innate immune defect would most likely be diagnosed in them?","explanation":null,"reference":"Justiz Vaillant AA, Ahmad F. Leukocyte adhesion deficiency. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 5, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539770/","responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukocyte adhesion deficiency (LAD)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common variable cell immunodeficiency (CVID)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4353,"text":"Which one of the following plasma proteins helps in the transport of free fatty acids in the blood stream?","explanation":null,"reference":"van der Vusse GJ. Albumin as fatty acid transporter. Drug Metabolism and Pharmacokinetics. Published 2009. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19745557/","responses":[{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"γ-globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4355,"text":"Which specific term is used when a biocide is able to kill bacteria?","explanation":null,"reference":"Calhoun C, Wermuth HR, Hall GA. Antibiotics. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 4, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535443/","responses":[{"text":"Bacteriostatic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bactericidal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibacteriotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cleaning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insecticide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4356,"text":"Which stage of P. falciparum is crescent shaped?","explanation":null,"reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 425.","responses":[{"text":"Oocyte stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporoite stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ring stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Schizont stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gametocyte stage","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4357,"text":"Which type of epidemiological method investigates and evaluates preventative and therapeutic measures?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Literature search","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preventative method","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Observational","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Descriptive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ecologic studies","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4358,"text":"Regarding β-thalassemia major, which of the following is the most relevant?","explanation":null,"reference":"Galanello R, Origa R. Beta-thalassemia. Orphanet Journal of Rare Diseases. Published May 21, 2010. Accessed June 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2893117/","responses":[{"text":"Iron overload is due to high levels of hepcidin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Manifests itself in-utero","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow transplantation at an early stage is the treatment of choice","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"With transfusions alone, survival into the sixth or seventh decade is possible","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia is due to decreased erythropoietin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4359,"text":"A 45-year-old man develops a myocardial infarction. His condition improves and he is discharged from the hospital. He is then prescribed 325 mg aspirin daily. This drug inhibits platelet aggregation by decreasing the production of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 118.","responses":[{"text":"Lipoxygenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboxane A₂","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Clotting factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclooxygenase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4360,"text":"A 55-year-old man is diagnosed with pulmonary embolism. He is admitted to the hospital and started on heparin therapy. The anticoagulant effect of this drug would be the most appropriately assessed by which of the following laboratory values?","explanation":null,"reference":"Uprichard J, Manning RA, Laffan MA. Monitoring heparin anticoagulation in the acute phase response. British Journal of Haematology. Published May 2010. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20230412/","responses":[{"text":"International normalized ratio (INR)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bleeding time","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin time (PT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4361,"text":"A 60-year-old man with severe chest pain is unresponsive to sublingual nitroglycerin. A thrombolytic therapy is initiated. If streptokinase is given to this patient, it may produce thrombolysis after binding which of the following proteins?","explanation":null,"reference":"Edwards Z, Nagalli S. Streptokinase. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 9, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553215/","responses":[{"text":"Antithrombin III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protein C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombomodulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasminogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4362,"text":"A 60-year-old woman had a mitral valve replacement and was placed on anticoagulants and prophylactics following her surgery. Five days after her surgery, she developed an erythematous rash on her thigh. Two days after the rash appeared, a large hemorrhage bulla then began to form in the area of the rash. Which of the following medications most likely caused the rash?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 124.","responses":[{"text":"Heparin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cefazoline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vancomycin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4363,"text":"A 7-year-old child has accidentally overdosed on iron supplements. Which of the following agents can be used as an antidote in this child?","explanation":null,"reference":"Velasquez J, Wray AA. Deferoxamine. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557654/","responses":[{"text":"Acetylcysteine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deferoxamine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phytonadione","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amyl nitrite","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4364,"text":"A child is suffering from chronic granulomatous disease. He has a genetic deficiency due to which he is more prone to infections, especially staphylococcal infection. Why is this?","explanation":null,"reference":"Giardino G, Cicalese MP, Delmonte O, et al. Nadph oxidase deficiency: a multisystem approach. Oxidative Medicine and Cellular Longevity. Published 2017. Accessed June 8, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5753020/","responses":[{"text":"Decreased superoxide radical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased phosphorylative ability","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lack of antibody coating","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lack of NADPH oxidase system","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Absence of cofactors such as iodine and bromine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4365,"text":"A middle-aged female with a known case of rheumatoid arthritis consulted her physician during her follow-up visit. On examination, she was found to have splenomegaly two fingers below the left costal margin. Lab results show anemia and neutropenia. She is currently on NSAIDs and low-dose steroid treatment. What is the cause of her splenomegaly?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 606.","responses":[{"text":"Malaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicimia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug induced","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Felty's syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4374,"text":"Which type of epidemiology interprets the therapeutic and preventive measures?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Descriptive epidemiology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Environmental epidemiology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Observational epidemiology","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Experimental epidemiology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Analytic epidemiology","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4376,"text":"What type of hypersensitivity reaction is involved in serum sickness?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 201.","responses":[{"text":"Type I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type III and IV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type IV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type III","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4379,"text":"In which of the following diseases are anti-neuronal antibodies formed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 225.","responses":[{"text":"Psoriasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bannwarth's syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatoid arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4381,"text":"What type of red blood cells are seen in iron deficiency anemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 652.","responses":[{"text":"Microcytic, hypochromic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrocytic, hypochromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normocytic, hyperchromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normocytic, normochromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microcytic, hyperchromic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4384,"text":"Once an inflammatory response is mediated by the complement activation, an acute increase in the levels of which of the following can be observed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 89.","responses":[{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"T-lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B-lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4386,"text":"What type of antibodies are produced in the Arthus reaction?","explanation":null,"reference":"Peng B, Wei M, Zhu FC, Li JX. The vaccines-associated Arthus reaction. Human Vaccines \u0026 Immunotherapeutics. Published May 3, 2019. Accessed June 7, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6930064/","responses":[{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4488,"text":"Which one of the following is the best non-invasive diagnostic test for iron deficiency anemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 652.","responses":[{"text":"Total iron-binding capacity test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum ferritin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipid profile","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood culture (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA1c test","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4498,"text":"Which of these results in the reduction of the formation of methemoglobin from hemoglobin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ludlow JT, Wilkerson RG, Nappe TM. Methemoglobinemia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 8, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537317/","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin E","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4509,"text":"A person undergoes ileal resection. After some days he develops weakness, shortness of breath, and anemia. Which anemia can it possibly be?","explanation":"After ileal resection, the absorption of vitamin B12 is impaired since the ileum is responsible for the absorption of this essential vitamin. Vitamin B12 is required for the synthesis of DNA and normal red blood cell maturation. Therefore, a deficiency of vitamin B12 leads to **megaloblastic anemia**.\r\n\r\nMegaloblastic anemia is characterized by the presence of large, immature red blood cells (megaloblasts) in the bone marrow. These cells have impaired DNA synthesis, leading to delayed maturation. The result is fewer and larger red blood cells in circulation.\r\n\r\nClinical manifestations of megaloblastic anemia include weakness, shortness of breath, and anemia symptoms due to decreased oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood. Other symptoms may include pale skin, fatigue, and neurological manifestations such as numbness and tingling in the extremities.\r\n\r\nSupplementation of vitamin B12 is necessary to correct the deficiency and alleviate the symptoms of megaloblastic anemia.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 45.","responses":[{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic blood loss anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pernicious anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4510,"text":"A 5-year-old girl accidentally touches a bowl of hot soup. Her right-hand skin develops erythema and blisters form on the pads of her fingers. What kind of inflammation is this?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Ulceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous inflammation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinoid inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4512,"text":"Myoglobin is a pigment. Which system of the body does it have a role in?","explanation":"**Myoglobin** is a pigment that plays a crucial role in the respiratory system. It is a protein found primarily in muscle cells, particularly in the skeletal and cardiac muscles. Myoglobin functions as an oxygen-binding molecule, storing and releasing oxygen within muscle tissues.\r\n\r\nDuring muscle contraction, oxygen is required to support the energy demands of the muscle cells. Myoglobin acts as an oxygen reservoir, allowing efficient oxygen delivery to the muscle cells. It has a higher affinity for oxygen compared to hemoglobin, enabling it to readily bind and release oxygen within the muscle fibers.\r\n\r\nThe presence of myoglobin in muscle tissues enhances the oxygen supply and utilization during exercise and periods of increased metabolic demand. This ensures adequate oxygen delivery for energy production and muscle function.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1078.","responses":[{"text":"Respiratory system","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Central nervous system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinary system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electron transport chain","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4514,"text":"A 12-year-old male is suffering from beta-thalassemia major. Which one of the following is the most important factor resulting in iron overload in his body?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 641, 651.","responses":[{"text":"Elevated hepcidin levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic blood transfusion and low hepcidin levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased hemolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic blood transfusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low hepcidin levels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4516,"text":"A pathologist examines a hemoglobin electrophoresis slide of a patient suffering from beta-thalassemia trait. Which hemoglobin will most likely be seen?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 641.","responses":[{"text":"HbA2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HbF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA1C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4518,"text":"Hemostasis is a means of preventing blood loss. Whenever an injury occurs, which one of the following is the first step towards clotting?","explanation":"**Vasoconstriction** is indeed the first step in hemostasis, triggered immediately after injury to blood vessels. When a blood vessel is damaged, the smooth muscle in its walls constricts, causing the vessel to narrow. This vasoconstriction serves two primary purposes in hemostasis.\r\n\r\nFirst, vasoconstriction reduces blood flow to the injured area, which helps to minimize blood loss. The constriction of the vessel lumen decreases the amount of blood flowing through the damaged vessel, thus decreasing the hydrostatic pressure and the force pushing blood out of the vessel.\r\n\r\nSecond, vasoconstriction helps to expose the damaged endothelium to the bloodstream for platelet adhesion and activation. As the vessel constricts, the exposed endothelial cells release substances that promote platelet adhesion and initiate the formation of the platelet plug.\r\n\r\nTherefore, vasoconstriction is an essential initial response that occurs in the early stages of hemostasis to reduce blood flow and facilitate platelet plug formation at the site of injury.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 477.","responses":[{"text":"Vasoconstriction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of platelet plug","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of coagulation cascade","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of fibrin plug","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retraction of the platelet plug","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4521,"text":"Which interleukin is required for the growth and proliferation of all the stem cells?","explanation":"**Interleukin-3 (IL-3)** is a cytokine that plays a crucial role in the growth and proliferation of stem cells. IL-3 is produced by various cells, including activated T cells and mast cells, and acts on hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow. \r\n\r\nIL-3 stimulates the production and differentiation of multiple blood cell lineages, including red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets. It acts as a growth factor for early progenitor cells, promoting their survival, proliferation, and differentiation into specific cell types. By supporting the growth of stem cells, IL-3 helps to maintain a healthy and functional hematopoietic system.\r\n\r\nWhile other interleukins, such as IL-1, IL-4, IL-5, and IL-2, also play important roles in immune regulation and hematopoiesis, IL-3 is specifically known for its broad effects on stem cell growth and proliferation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Interleukin-5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4523,"text":"What is the function of the Fc portion of the antibody?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Blocking ligand-receptor interactions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phagocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antigen binding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complement fixation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Class switiching","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4526,"text":"What are the antigens that are expressed in the fetal state and in the tumor cells called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 311.","responses":[{"text":"Oncofetal antigens","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fraternal antigens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oncofetal maternal antigens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neonatal antigens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cryptic antigens","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4527,"text":"Deficiency of which enzyme is the cause of hereditary coproporphyria (HCP)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Martásek P. Hereditary coproporphyria. Seminars in Liver Disease. Published 1998. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9516675/","responses":[{"text":"Ferrochelatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Porphobilinogen deaminase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coproporphyrinogen oxidase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphobilinogen oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen-III synthase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4528,"text":"For the routine blood sample test in the lab upon the centrifugation of the blood, a yellow color fluid is obtained\r\nthat differs from the plasma in one component. Which of these would most likely be that component?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 480.","responses":[{"text":"Sugar/carbohydrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inorganic components/electrolytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Globulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4531,"text":"Which of the following is true about the lymph nodes?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 453.","responses":[{"text":"There is a dense medulla present","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reticular fibers are present in parenchyma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral subcapsular sinus is present","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"B-cells are present in paracortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of the options are true","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4534,"text":"During the development of red blood cells, a cell is formed having 34% of hemoglobin content, a condensed nucleus, with its endoplasmic reticulum reabsorbed. Which of the following is that cell?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Basophilic erythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polychromatophilic erythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reticulocyte","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythrocyte","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4535,"text":"A person is suffering from a disease but he is healthy and shows no signs and symptoms because of preventative measures he took for his health post-diagnosis. What type of prevention is this?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kisling LA, M Das J. Prevention strategies. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 11, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537222/","responses":[{"text":"Primary prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Early detection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary prevention","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tertiary prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rehabilitation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4536,"text":"Which substance is present on the plasma membrane of platelets that does not let them bind to the normal\r\nendothelium but instead adhere to the damaged vessels; especially to their exposed collagen?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 477.","responses":[{"text":"Coat of glycoprotein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Actin and myosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombosthenin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4537,"text":"In a sample of blood, antisera A and B show agglutination while antiserum D doesn’t. What would the blood type be?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 472, 473.","responses":[{"text":"A positive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"O positive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"O negative","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"AB positive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"AB negative","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4538,"text":"If the genotype of a person is OO, what would the phenotype be?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 472.","responses":[{"text":"Agglutinogen A, agglutinin A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No agglutinogens, agglutinins A and B","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Agglutinogens A \u0026 B, agglutinins A \u0026 B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Agglutinogens B, A agglutinins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No agglutinogens, agglutinin A","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4539,"text":"Hemoglobin is broken down into heme and globin followed by the conversion of biliverdin into bilirubin. Inside the hepatic system, what does bilirubin gets conjugated with?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 852-853.","responses":[{"text":"Ascorbic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulfate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucuronic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4540,"text":"A woman with damage to the mitral valve of the heart is placed on warfarin therapy. Which of the following may be used to follow the anticoagulant activity?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 488.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated partial thromboplastin clotting time (aPTT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bleeding time","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The prothrombin time test/ International normalized ratio (PT/INR)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood picture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4541,"text":"Which of the following mucin antigens is present in both ovarian and breast cancers?","explanation":"**MUC-1** is the mucin antigen that is present in both ovarian and breast cancers. MUC-1, also known as **mucin 1** or **CA 15-3**, is a glycoprotein that is aberrantly expressed in various types of cancers, including ovarian and breast cancers.\r\n\r\nMUC-1 plays a role in protecting and lubricating epithelial surfaces. In normal tissues, it is expressed on the apical surface of glandular and ductal epithelial cells. However, in cancer cells, MUC-1 is overexpressed and undergoes structural changes, leading to increased cell adhesion, invasion, and metastasis.\r\n\r\nThe detection of MUC-1 antigen in serum can be used as a tumor marker for monitoring disease progression and response to treatment in ovarian and breast cancers. It is commonly measured using the CA 15-3 assay for breast cancer and the CA-125 assay for ovarian cancer.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 312.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CA19-9","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CA-125","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MUC-1","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4542,"text":"Which of the following lymphocyte is involved in frontline defense against tumor cells without any previous exposure?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Natural killer (NK) cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotoxic T-lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CD4+T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CD8+T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B-lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4543,"text":"The main contributor to the production of erythropoietin is the kidney. Which of the following is another organ that is also involved in the production of erythropoietin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 442.","responses":[{"text":"Adrenal medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Long bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4544,"text":"During the development of the spleen, mesenchymal cells are present between which layers?","explanation":"During the development of the spleen, mesenchymal cells are present between the **two layers of the dorsal mesogastrium**. The dorsal mesogastrium is a double-layered peritoneal fold that extends from the posterior abdominal wall to the developing stomach. It divides the abdominal cavity into the greater and lesser peritoneal sacs.\r\n\r\nWithin the dorsal mesogastrium, the mesenchymal cells undergo differentiation and give rise to the various components of the developing spleen. These components include the splenic parenchyma, blood vessels, and the connective tissue framework.\r\n\r\nAs development progresses, the dorsal mesogastrium undergoes further modifications, leading to the formation of the lienorenal ligament and the attachment of the spleen to the posterior abdominal wall.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 237.","responses":[{"text":"The two layers of ventral mesogastrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal mesogastrium and septum transversarium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral and dorsal mesogastrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral mesogastrium and septum transversarium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The two layers of dorsal mesogastrium","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4545,"text":"When the total storage iron is much greater than the apoferritin storage pool, the extra iron is stored in an insoluble form. This form is known as which of the following?","explanation":"**Hemosiderin** is an aggregate of ferritin molecules that have become partially denatured and insoluble. It is found in tissues and cells involved in iron storage, such as the liver, spleen, and bone marrow.\r\n\r\nHemosiderin appears as golden-brown granules when stained and is a visual marker of iron overload or excessive iron deposition in tissues. It represents an accumulated iron reserve that can be mobilized when needed.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, ferritin is the soluble form of iron storage. It is a protein complex that binds and sequesters iron in a non-toxic form. Ferritin serves as the primary intracellular storage for iron, while hemosiderin acts as a backup storage system when ferritin levels are overwhelmed.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 445.","responses":[{"text":"Ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4546,"text":"A woman's hemoglobin level is 15 g/100ml. How much oxygen will be present in 100ml?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 524.","responses":[{"text":"25 ml","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"15 ml","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 ml","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"30 ml","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"40 ml","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4547,"text":"Which of the following factors is involved in the prevention of the spread of the clot to nearby tissues?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.","responses":[{"text":"Thrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombin and thrombomodulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombomodulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasminogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4548,"text":"Which of the following is not a common pathway for the spread of metastasis?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Seeding of cavities","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Local invasion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematogenous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphatics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4549,"text":"The membrane of red blood cells is covered with antibodies that allow which of the following to consume them after they are worn out?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 445.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4550,"text":"At which stage do the cancer cells undergo apoptosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 57, 1155.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Before M","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"After G1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"After S","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At restriction point","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4551,"text":"Which of the following is the cause for graft rejection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 233.","responses":[{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotoxic T cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CD4+ cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4552,"text":"A man was brought into the outpatient department (OPD) after a few hours of having a high-grade fever and cough. His white blood cells count is 13 000/μl (i.e. \u003e7000), platelets is 310,000/mm^3, hemoglobin is 14 g/dL and RBC count is 4.5 million/mm^3. Which leukocyte would be present in abundance here?","explanation":null,"reference":"Rosales C. Neutrophil: a cell with many roles in inflammation or several cell types? Frontiers in Physiology. Published February 20, 2018. Accessed June 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5826082/","responses":[{"text":"T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"B-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4553,"text":"Within how many hours is the epithelialization of the suture wounds completed?","explanation":"**Explanation:**\r\nThe process of epithelialization refers to the migration and proliferation of epithelial cells to cover and close a wound. In the case of suture wounds, the epithelialization process plays a crucial role in the healing and closure of the wound.\r\n\r\nEpithelialization typically starts within the first 24 hours of injury and continues for several days. By approximately 72 hours (3 days), the majority of suture wounds undergo significant epithelialization. During this time, the epithelial cells migrate from the wound edges and proliferate to form a new layer of epithelium over the wound surface. The newly formed epithelium gradually covers the wound, sealing it off from the external environment.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that the exact duration of epithelialization may vary depending on various factors such as the size and depth of the wound, the individual's overall health, and any underlying medical conditions. However, as a general guideline, 72 hours is considered a reasonable timeframe for significant epithelialization to occur in suture wounds.","reference":"Alhajj M, Goyal A. Physiology, granulation tissue. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 11, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554402/","responses":[{"text":"72 hours","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"24 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"48 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"36 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"96 hours","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11722,"text":"The red pulp of the spleen contains which one of the following?","explanation":"The spleen is divided into two main compartments: the **red pulp** and the **white pulp**. The **red pulp** is responsible for filtering and processing blood, while the **white pulp** is involved in immune responses.\r\n\r\nWithin the red pulp, there are **sinusoids** and **cords of Billroth**. The sinusoids are vascular channels lined by endothelial cells and are involved in the filtration of blood. The cords of Billroth are reticular tissue structures that contain macrophages, lymphocytes, plasma cells, and erythrocytes. These cords help to remove damaged or old red blood cells, as well as pathogens and cellular debris, from the circulation.\r\n\r\nThe white pulp of the spleen is primarily composed of periarteriolar lymphoid sheaths (PALS) surrounding central arterioles. The PALS contain T-lymphocytes and are involved in initiating immune responses to antigens.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 286.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central arteriole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cords of bilroth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"PALS (periarteriolar lymphoid sheaths)","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

